      Merger arb v. Lina Khan
   =20
 =20

One idea that you sometimes hear is that, when the broad stock market stead=
ily goes up each year, that is=C2=A0bad=C2=A0for investment managers. If th=
e S&P 500 index just goes up 15% per year, then anyone can do great by buyi=
ng an index fund, and the benefits of picking the best stocks are lower. Hi=
ghly paid active managers distinguish themselves more in choppy markets, wh=
ere picking the right stocks is distinctly more valuable than picking the w=
rong ones.
Similarly you could imagine an antitrust enforcement regime in which the US=
 Federal Trade Commission almost never tries to block mergers, except in th=
e most egregious cases of monopoly power. In this regime:
=09Most mergers, once announced, will close: The FTC won=E2=80=99t step in =
to block them.=09If the FTC=C2=A0does=C2=A0step in to block a merger, the d=
eal=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0close: The FTC only tries to block egregious me=
rgers, so if it tries, that means its case is strong and it will win in cou=
rt.=09(Also, the egregious mergers mostly=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t be announced:=
=C2=A0The FTC=E2=80=99s approach is predictable, and companies won=E2=80=99=
t bother to sign merger agreements that they know the FTC will try to block=
, since they=E2=80=99ll lose.)

This makes mergers very predictable, which is probably good for financial m=
arkets and investors. It is in some loose sense good for merger arbitrage f=
unds, which bet on mergers closing: The mergers they bet on will mostly clo=
se, and the ones that won=E2=80=99t close are pretty obvious and they can a=
void those.=C2=A0
But it is also bad=C2=A0for merger arbitrageurs, because the returns to ski=
ll go down. If a merger is announced, that means it will close, which means=
 that the target=E2=80=99s stock price will jump up close to the deal price=
 right away, and you can=E2=80=99t make any money doing merger arbitrage. E=
veryone knows =E2=80=9Cif a merger is announced at $20 per share, the stock=
 is worth $20 per share,=E2=80=9D so the stock goes to $20 per share right =
away, and your special knowledge about mergers is worthless.
On the other hand you could imagine an antitrust enforcement regime in whic=
h the FTC tries to block=C2=A0every=C2=A0merger, whether or not it has good=
 arguments. In this regime, the FTC would often lose in court, but would so=
metimes win. Every time a deal is announced, the target=E2=80=99s stock wou=
ld go up (=E2=80=9Cooh they=E2=80=99ll pay $20 per share!=E2=80=9D), and th=
en the FTC would announce a lawsuit and the stock would go down (=E2=80=9Co=
oh the FTC is blocking the deal!=E2=80=9D), and then the stock would bounce=
 around on the results of the court case.=C2=A0
This is great for merger arbs! If they=E2=80=99re good! The returns to skil=
l =E2=80=94=C2=A0to reading FTC complaints and using your expertise to know=
 which mergers will close and which will be blocked =E2=80=94=C2=A0go way u=
p. You buy the deals that will close (and double down when the FTC sues and=
 the stock drops) and avoid the deals that won=E2=80=99t; you use skill to =
generate alpha, rather than just being a passive index investor in every de=
al.
Obviously the actual FTC does not sue to block=C2=A0every=C2=A0deal, but it=
 has definitely turned the dial toward blocking more deals and making more =
aggressive arguments, which probably annoys some merger arbs in their day-t=
o-day lives but in the long run makes their lives better. The  Wall Street =
Journal reports:

The efforts by Federal Trade Commission Chair Lina Khan to protect Main Str=
eet are inadvertently enriching some on Wall Street, generating outsize pro=
fits for Pentwater Capital Management and other large hedge funds that bet =
on merger deals.
Florida-based Pentwater stands to be a large winner from the FTC=E2=80=99s =
recent failed bid to block the Amgen-Horizon deal. It built a stake of almo=
st 7% in Horizon after the drugmaker began fielding takeover interest last =
year.=C2=A0
Pentwater is estimated to have scored around $100 million on its Horizon tr=
ade on paper, according to an analysis of the hedge fund=E2=80=99s public f=
ilings. =E2=80=A6
D.E. Shaw Group is also among the funds that stood their ground following t=
he FTC lawsuit against Horizon. The New York-based firm steadily increased =
its position and currently holds more than $500 million in the shares, fili=
ngs show. Other funds that bet on Horizon include Farallon Capital Manageme=
nt and HBK Capital Management, according to public filings.
=E2=80=9CBecause of the FTC=E2=80=99s lawsuit, we have had the ability to t=
ake something that would have made tens of millions of dollars and instead =
make many, many times that amount,=E2=80=9D said Matt Halbower, Pentwater=
=E2=80=99s chief executive. =E2=80=A6
Since its inception, Pentwater, which oversees close to $5 billion, has ave=
raged a net return of more than 11% annually, according to a person familia=
r with the matter. By comparison, the HFRI Event-Driven Index generated an =
annualized net return of 4.47% from January 2007 through August 2023, accor=
ding to research firm HFR.

Yes right if you are good at merger arb you want some dispersion in outcome=
s.=C2=A0Pentwater also =E2=80=9Clast year scooped up shares of Twitter, now=
 X, in a wager that Elon Musk would ultimately acquire the company,=E2=80=
