gulation SHO, the regulatory framework designed to address abusive short se=
lling practices, which requires broker-dealers to mark sale orders as long,=
 short, or short exempt. These records are routinely used by regulators in =
policing prohibited short selling activity. To settle the SEC=E2=80=99s cha=
rges, Miami-based Citadel Securities agreed to pay a $7 million penalty.
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, for a five-year period, it is estimat=
ed that Citadel Securities incorrectly marked millions of orders, inaccurat=
ely denoting that certain short sales were long sales and vice versa. The S=
EC=E2=80=99s order finds that the inaccurate marks resulted from a coding e=
rror in Citadel Securities=E2=80=99s automated trading system and that the =
firm provided the inaccurate data to regulators, including the SEC during t=
his period.
=E2=80=9CCompliance with the order marking requirements of Reg SHO is a key=
 component of regulatory efforts to curtail abusive market practices, inclu=
ding =E2=80=98naked=E2=80=99 short selling,=E2=80=9D said Mark Cave, Associ=
ate Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =E2=80=9CThis ac=
tion against Citadel Securities demonstrates that a broker-dealer=E2=80=99s=
 failure to comply with the requirements of Reg SHO can have negative downs=
tream consequences on the accuracy of the firm=E2=80=99s electronic records=
, including its electronic blue sheet reporting, depriving the Commission o=
