No, no, still kidding, they didn=E2=80=99t do any naked short selling.=C2=
=A0Basically Citadel Securities is a broker-dealer, and sometimes customers=
 will come in and say =E2=80=9Cbuy me 10,000 shares of XYZ stock over the c=
ourse of the day, use your judgment, get the best price.=E2=80=9D And so Ci=
tadel Securities will buy 10 shares here, 20 shares there, etc., until it g=
ets to 10,000, delivering the shares to the customer and charging it the pr=
ices it pays.
Usually Citadel Securities will buy 10 shares, sell the customer 10 shares,=
 buy 20 shares, sell the customer 20 shares, etc. But some customers do not=
 want to be pinged every few seconds, and they will tell Citadel Securities=
 =E2=80=9Cjust buy me the 10,000 shares and tell me when you=E2=80=99re don=
e; don=E2=80=99t tell me about every little trade.=E2=80=9D And so Citadel =
Securities will buy 10 shares, make a mental note that they=E2=80=99re for =
the customer, buy 20 more shares, make another mental note, etc., until it =
gets up to 10,000 shares and pings the customer saying =E2=80=9Cwe finished=
 the 10,000 shares, here you go.=E2=80=9D
Fine. But for five years, there was a glitch in Citadel Securities=E2=80=99=
 little mental notes. The part of Citadel Securities=E2=80=99=C2=A0computer=
=C2=A0that kept track of its positions =E2=80=94=C2=A0for, among other thin=
gs, short-selling order-marking purposes =E2=80=94=C2=A0did not get the lit=
tle mental notes for the interim trades. One part of Citadel Securities=E2=
=80=99 computer=C2=A0saw it buy 10 shares and said =E2=80=9Cah we own 10 sh=
ares,=E2=80=9D and then it bought 20 more shares and was like =E2=80=9Cah n=
ow we own 30 shares,=E2=80=9D and so on, until right before the order was f=
inished it was like =E2=80=9Cah we own 9,900 shares=E2=80=9D or whatever. A=
nd then it would buy the last 100 shares and wiser logic would step in and =
say =E2=80=9Cnow we own 10,000 shares, but we have sold 10,000 shares to th=
e customer, so we=E2=80=99re back to zero shares.=E2=80=9D Citadel Securiti=
es did the=C2=A0trade=C2=A0correctly. But before it=C2=A0finished=C2=A0the =
trade, it thought that it=C2=A0owned=C2=A0all of the shares, whereas really=
 it was selling them to the customer. It did not really own them at all.
  [1]

And so if Citadel Securities was halfway through working this order, its co=
mputer would think it owned 5,000 shares. And then if some other part of Ci=
tadel Securities wanted to=C2=A0sell=C2=A0100 shares of XYZ, for market-mak=
ing or whatever purposes, the computer would think =E2=80=9C5,000 minus 100=
