One somewhat plausible view of artificial intelligence in investment bankin=
g is:
=09A robot can do most of the work that first-year investment banking analy=
sts do: preparing financial models from templates, choosing comparable comp=
anies, formatting pitchbooks, cutting league-table data in exactly the righ=
t way to make their bank No. 1, etc.=09A robot cannot do most of the work t=
hat senior managing directors do: meeting clients face-to-face with a firm =
handshake and good eye contact, asking them about their kids and their golf=
 game, giving strategic advice about merger negotiations and financing opti=
ons, exercising good judgment, tossing aside the pitchbook that the analyst=
s spent sleepless nights preparing to have a heart-to-heart chat about what=
ever=E2=80=99s on the client=E2=80=99s mind,=C2=A0etc.

I am not sure that that=E2=80=99s right? Judging by actually existing large=
 language models, I would not be stunned if it was easier to program a robo=
t to give confident and sage-sounding strategic advice, and remember the cl=
ients=E2=80=99 kids=E2=80=99 names, than it is to program a robot to build =
financial models with no tolerance for error, or perform the dark arts of l=
eague-table manipulation. But broadly speaking the junior bankers do some c=
ombination of analytical and grunt work, while the senior bankers provide t=
he strategic vision and the personal touch, and it=C2=A0seems=C2=A0like the=
 former would be easier to automate than the latter.
Investment banking is an odd sort of apprenticeship business in that=C2=A0y=
ou spend a few years doing the analytical and grunt work=C2=A0as training=
=C2=A0to be strategic and personal. It is not obvious=C2=A0that preparing p=
itchbooks and discounted cash flow models would be good preparation for giv=
ing clients firm handshakes and nuanced negotiating advice, but that is the=
 way it=E2=80=99s done.
  [3]
=C2=A0Some (large) number of good junior analysts will not make it as senio=
r investment bankers, because they are good at spreadsheets and formatting =
but bad at strategy and handshakes. Some (smaller) number of bad junior ana=
lysts will wash out because they are bad at spreadsheets and formatting, bu=
t if they had scraped through they would have been amazing managing directo=
rs, with an ingratiating manner and a good grasp of what clients want. You =
need both qualities, in sequence, for some reason.
But if you give all the analytical and grunt work to the robot then how do =
you mold senior investment bankers? I don=E2=80=99t know. Insider=E2=80=99s=
