One basic idea in environmental, social and governance investing is that yo=
u should allocate much (100%?) of your investment portfolio to companies wi=
th good ESG credentials, and less (0%?) of your portfolio to companies with=
 bad ESG credentials. You have some reason for liking ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e  main ones are =E2=80=9CI think I will make the world a better place by a=
llocating capital to green companies and withholding capital from dirty one=
s,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI think that ESG risk factors are important for lon=
g-run financial returns, so companies with good ESG credentials will outper=
form those with bad ESG credentials=E2=80=9D
  [4]
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that reason counsels you to put more money in good ESG =
stocks and less (or zero) money in bad ESG stocks.
But zero is a pretty arbitrary cutoff. If it is good to put 100% of your mo=
ney in good ESG stocks and 0% in bad ESG stocks, then isn=E2=80=99t it even=
 better to put 120% of your money in good ESG stocks and negative 20% in ba=
d ESG stocks? Shouldn=E2=80=99t you=C2=A0short=C2=A0companies with bad ESG =
credentials? I mean, again, your reasons for liking ESG might vary, but eit=
her way
  [5]
:
=09If you think it is good for the world to give capital to good ESG compan=
ies and deny it to bad ESG companies, then shorting the stocks of bad ESG c=
ompanies raises their cost of capital even more, so you should do it.=09If =
you think that bad ESG companies face underappreciated financial risks that=
 will drive down their stock prices, then betting against them should be lu=
crative.
  [6]



This is somewhat controversial, because investing actual money in environme=
ntally friendly companies seems like a straightforwardly good thing to do, =
while betting against environmentally bad companies seems like, you know, f=
inancial engineering. I  wrote once:
It feels very=C2=A0financial, using the abstract workings of the financial =
system to make bold claims about a real-world result. If you are, say, Jim =
Chanos and you run a short-focused fund, presumably the overall carbon impa=
ct of your portfolio is very negative (because most companies, in any indus=
try, are using some carbon to make stuff or fly to meetings or whatever, an=
d so if you=E2=80=99re shorting a bunch of companies you have a negative po=
sition on a lot of carbon use). Could Jim Chanos just like fly in circles i=
n a private jet while eating beef and taking long showers and saying =E2=80=
=9CI am the greatest climate hero in the history of the world,=E2=80=9D bec=
ause of his short selling? Maybe?
A further, more nuanced version is: Is it good ESG to short companies that=
=C2=A0claim=C2=A0to be good at ESG, but that you think are actually bad at =
ESG? Not forthrightly dirty coal companies, but energy companies that prete=
nd to be green and aren=E2=80=99t? A classic sort of short selling is that =
a company reports good financial results, its stock goes up, you investigat=
e and determine that the company is doing accounting fraud, you short it, y=
ou expose the fraud, the stock goes to zero and you get rich. This is all v=
ery intuitive: The stock price is high because people think the company is =
profitable, you bet that it isn=E2=80=99t, you win. The mechanism of the tr=
ade is that a stock price is the present value of the company=E2=80=99s fut=
ure cash flows, and if the cash flows are fraud then the price is probably =
too high.
But what if the ESG is fraud? Should you short bad-but-pretending-to-be-goo=
d ESG companies, on a theory like =E2=80=9Ca stock price is partly the mark=
et=E2=80=99s=C2=A0valuation=C2=A0of a company=E2=80=99s ESG behavior, and i=
f the company=E2=80=99s ESG behavior is fake then the price is probably too=
 high=E2=80=9D? I mean? It makes some sense, right? The stock price is not=
=C2=A0just=C2=A0the present value of the future cash flows. It=E2=80=99s al=
so the present value of what people will pay you for the stock. And if peop=
le mostly want to pay for good ESG performance, then the fake-ESG stocks wi=
ll have high prices now and low prices when they are found out.
Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Ishika Mookerjee and Sheryl Tian Tong Lee r=
