  [1] Importantly, what this means is that the trade was a =E2=80=9Criskles=
s principal=E2=80=9D trade and the customer paid the prices Citadel Securit=
ies paid. If Citadel Securities was buying 10,000 shares for its own invent=
ory, and then at the end it sold all 10,000 to the customer at the price at=
 the time, then it kind of did own those shares along the way. But the way =
these trades worked is that Citadel Securities got paid the actual prices i=
t paid along the way, so at the time it bought 10 shares it *really had* al=
ready sold them at the price it paid (plus some commissions, spread or what=
ever).


  [2] The delay was up to several hours, which means that Citadel Securitie=
s knew its true position fairly quickly and, if it needed to borrow shares =
before settlement, it could. Also, the naked short selling rules include an=
 exception from the borrowing requirement for =E2=80=9Cshort sales effected=
 by a market maker in connection with bona-fide market making activities in=
 the security,=E2=80=9D which I suspect would apply to most of Citadel Secu=
rities=E2=80=99 trading.


  [3] I realize that in 2023 the analyst program is *really* training to qu=
it and work in private equity, but senior investment bankers have to come f=
rom *somewhere*, and it=E2=80=99s mostly from the ranks of junior investmen=
t bankers.


  [4] A third might be =E2=80=9CI think that ESG funds will continue to bec=
ome more popular, so more money will pile into them, so in the short term g=
ood ESG stocks will go up, so I want to buy them now for a trade.=E2=80=9D


  [5] If you think that ESG funds will become more popular so in the short =
term good ESG stocks will go up and bad ESG stocks will go down (previous f=
ootnote) then, again, short the bad ones now.


  [6] Short selling and long buying are not fully symmetrical and =E2=80=9C=
ESG factors represent long-term risks=E2=80=9D is arguably a good reason to=
 buy good ESG stocks and hold them for the long term, but a bad reason to s=
hort bad ESG stocks, because short selling involves more short-term risks.


