<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One idea that you sometimes hear is that, when=
 the broad stock market steadily goes up each year, that is=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=
=A0</em>for investment managers. If the S&amp;P 500 index just goes up 15% =
per year, then anyone can do great by buying an index fund, and the benefit=
s of picking the best stocks are lower. Highly paid active managers disting=
uish themselves more in choppy markets, where picking the right stocks is d=
istinctly more valuable than picking the wrong ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly you could imagine an antitrust enfor=
cement regime in which the US Federal Trade Commission almost never tries t=
o block mergers, except in the most egregious cases of monopoly power. In t=
his regime:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most mergers, once announced, will clo=
se: The FTC won=E2=80=99t step in to block them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">If the FTC=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>step in to block a merger=
, the deal=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>close: The FTC only tries to bl=
ock egregious mergers, so if it tries, that means its case is strong and it=
 will win in court.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">(Also, the egr=
egious mergers mostly=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t be announced:=C2=A0</em>The FT=
C=E2=80=99s approach is predictable, and companies won=E2=80=99t bother to =
sign merger agreements that they know the FTC will try to block, since they=
=E2=80=99ll lose.)</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This makes mergers very predictable, which is =
probably good for financial markets and investors. It is in some loose sens=
e good for merger arbitrage funds, which bet on mergers closing: The merger=
s they bet on will mostly close, and the ones that won=E2=80=99t close are =
pretty obvious and they can avoid those.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is also <em>bad=C2=A0</em>for merger ar=
bitrageurs, because the returns to skill go down. If a merger is announced,=
 that means it will close, which means that the target=E2=80=99s stock pric=
e will jump up close to the deal price right away, and you can=E2=80=99t ma=
ke any money doing merger arbitrage. Everyone knows =E2=80=9Cif a merger is=
 announced at $20 per share, the stock is worth $20 per share,=E2=80=9D so =
the stock goes to $20 per share right away, and your special knowledge abou=
t mergers is worthless.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand you could imagine an antitru=
st enforcement regime in which the FTC tries to block=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0<=
/em>merger, whether or not it has good arguments. In this regime, the FTC w=
ould often lose in court, but would sometimes win. Every time a deal is ann=
ounced, the target=E2=80=99s stock would go up (=E2=80=9Cooh they=E2=80=99l=
l pay $20 per share!=E2=80=9D), and then the FTC would announce a lawsuit a=
nd the stock would go down (=E2=80=9Cooh the FTC is blocking the deal!=E2=
=80=9D), and then the stock would bounce around on the results of the court=
 case.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is great for merger arbs! If they=E2=80=
=99re good! The returns to skill =E2=80=94=C2=A0to reading FTC complaints a=
nd using your expertise to know which mergers will close and which will be =
blocked =E2=80=94=C2=A0go way up. You buy the deals that will close (and do=
uble down when the FTC sues and the stock drops) and avoid the deals that w=
on=E2=80=99t; you use skill to generate alpha, rather than just being a pas=
sive index investor in every deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously the actual FTC does not sue to block=
=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>deal, but it has definitely turned the dial towar=
d blocking more deals and making more aggressive arguments, which probably =
annoys some merger arbs in their day-to-day lives but in the long run makes=
 their lives better. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS91cy1uZXdzL2xhdy90aGUtaGVk=
Z2UtZnVuZC10aGF0LW1hZGUtYS1raWxsaW5nLWJldHRpbmctYWdhaW5zdC1saW5hLWtoYW4tZDV=
iMzk1YjE_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdbbbf0e8" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The efforts by Federal Trade Commission Chair =
Lina Khan to protect Main Street are inadvertently enriching some on Wall S=
treet, generating outsize profits for Pentwater Capital Management and othe=
r large hedge funds that bet on merger deals.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Florida-based Pentwater stands to be a large w=
inner from the FTC=E2=80=99s recent failed bid to block the Amgen-Horizon d=
eal. It built a stake of almost 7% in Horizon after the drugmaker began fie=
lding takeover interest last year.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pentwater is estimated to have scored around $=
100 million on its Horizon trade on paper, according to an analysis of the =
hedge fund=E2=80=99s public filings. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">D.E. Shaw Group is also among the funds that s=
tood their ground following the FTC lawsuit against Horizon. The New York-b=
ased firm steadily increased its position and currently holds more than $50=
0 million in the shares, filings show. Other funds that bet on Horizon incl=
ude Farallon Capital Management and HBK Capital Management, according to pu=
blic filings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CBecause of the FTC=E2=80=99s lawsuit,=
 we have had the ability to take something that would have made tens of mil=
lions of dollars and instead make many, many times that amount,=E2=80=9D sa=
id Matt Halbower, Pentwater=E2=80=99s chief executive. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since its inception, Pentwater, which oversees=
 close to $5 billion, has averaged a net return of more than 11% annually, =
according to a person familiar with the matter. By comparison, the HFRI Eve=
nt-Driven Index generated an annualized net return of 4.47% from January 20=
07 through August 2023, according to research firm HFR.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right if you are good at merger arb you wa=
nt some dispersion in outcomes.=C2=A0Pentwater also =E2=80=9Clast year scoo=
ped up shares of Twitter, now X, in a wager that Elon Musk would ultimately=
 acquire the company,=E2=80=9D another situation where it was helpful to be=
 able to notice that Musk=E2=80=99s case for getting out of the deal <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTgvZWxvbi13YW5=
0cy10by1maWdodC10aGUtYm90cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTI2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
