<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did the US Securities and Exchange Commission =
catch Citadel doing naked short selling? Ahahaha no, come on, I would never=
 say a thing like that. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvM=
jAyMy0xOTI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b3e1586" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> It was Citadel Secur=
ities</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [Friday=
] announced settled charges against broker-dealer Citadel Securities LLC fo=
r violating a provision of Regulation SHO, the regulatory framework designe=
d to address abusive short selling practices, which requires broker-dealers=
 to mark sale orders as long, short, or short exempt. These records are rou=
tinely used by regulators in policing prohibited short selling activity. To=
 settle the SEC=E2=80=99s charges, Miami-based Citadel Securities agreed to=
 pay a $7 million penalty.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, for a fi=
ve-year period, it is estimated that Citadel Securities incorrectly marked =
millions of orders, inaccurately denoting that certain short sales were lon=
g sales and vice versa. The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that the inaccurate m=
arks resulted from a coding error in Citadel Securities=E2=80=99s automated=
 trading system and that the firm provided the inaccurate data to regulator=
s, including the SEC during this period.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCompliance with the order marking req=
uirements of Reg SHO is a key component of regulatory efforts to curtail ab=
usive market practices, including =E2=80=98naked=E2=80=99 short selling,=E2=
=80=9D said Mark Cave, Associate Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of =
Enforcement. =E2=80=9CThis action against Citadel Securities demonstrates t=
hat a broker-dealer=E2=80=99s failure to comply with the requirements of Re=
g SHO can have negative downstream consequences on the accuracy of the firm=
=E2=80=99s electronic records, including its electronic blue sheet reportin=
g, depriving the Commission of important information about the markets it r=
egulates.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, no, still kidding, they didn=E2=80=99t do =
any naked short selling.=C2=A0Basically Citadel Securities is a broker-deal=
er, and sometimes customers will come in and say =E2=80=9Cbuy me 10,000 sha=
res of XYZ stock over the course of the day, use your judgment, get the bes=
t price.=E2=80=9D And so Citadel Securities will buy 10 shares here, 20 sha=
res there, etc., until it gets to 10,000, delivering the shares to the cust=
omer and charging it the prices it pays.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually Citadel Securities will buy 10 shares,=
 sell the customer 10 shares, buy 20 shares, sell the customer 20 shares, e=
tc. But some customers do not want to be pinged every few seconds, and they=
 will tell Citadel Securities =E2=80=9Cjust buy me the 10,000 shares and te=
ll me when you=E2=80=99re done; don=E2=80=99t tell me about every little tr=
ade.=E2=80=9D And so Citadel Securities will buy 10 shares, make a mental n=
ote that they=E2=80=99re for the customer, buy 20 more shares, make another=
 mental note, etc., until it gets up to 10,000 shares and pings the custome=
r saying =E2=80=9Cwe finished the 10,000 shares, here you go.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. But for five years, there was a glitch i=
n Citadel Securities=E2=80=99 little mental notes. The part of Citadel Secu=
rities=E2=80=99=C2=A0computer=C2=A0that kept track of its positions =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0for, among other things, short-selling order-marking purposes =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0did not get the little mental notes for the interim trades. One=
 part of Citadel Securities=E2=80=99 computer=C2=A0saw it buy 10 shares and=
 said =E2=80=9Cah we own 10 shares,=E2=80=9D and then it bought 20 more sha=
res and was like =E2=80=9Cah now we own 30 shares,=E2=80=9D and so on, unti=
l right before the order was finished it was like =E2=80=9Cah we own 9,900 =
shares=E2=80=9D or whatever. And then it would buy the last 100 shares and =
wiser logic would step in and say =E2=80=9Cnow we own 10,000 shares, but we=
 have sold 10,000 shares to the customer, so we=E2=80=99re back to zero sha=
res.=E2=80=9D Citadel Securities did the=C2=A0<em>trade=C2=A0</em>correctly=
. But before it=C2=A0<em>finished=C2=A0</em>the trade, it thought that it=
=C2=A0<em>owned=C2=A0</em>all of the shares, whereas really it was selling =
them to the customer. It did not really own them at all.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if Citadel Securities was halfway throu=
gh working this order, its computer would think it owned 5,000 shares. And =
then if some other part of Citadel Securities wanted to=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0=
</em>100 shares of XYZ, for market-making or whatever purposes, the compute=
r would think =E2=80=9C5,000 minus 100 is 4,900, which is a positive number=
, so this is a=C2=A0<em>long sale</em>,=E2=80=9D a sale of stock Citadel Se=
curities=C2=A0<em>owned</em>. So the computer would mark it as a long sale.=
 But=C2=A0<em>really</em>=C2=A0the math is =E2=80=9C5,000 shares we bought =
minus 5,000 shares we sold to the client equals zero, minus 100 is negative=
 100, so this is a short sale,=E2=80=9D so the computer should have marked =
it as a short sale. But it didn=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Citadel Securities sometimes reported t=
hat it was doing long sales when it was really doing short sales, which is =
a no-no, and the sort of thing that sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMTMvbmFrZWQtc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVyLWdldHMtaW=
4tdHJvdWJsZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTI2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76515f8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> lands people in trouble for=
 naked short selling</a>. Ordinarily, when you sell stock short, you need t=
o check that you can borrow the shares that you are selling before doing th=
e trade. But if you think (or report) that you already=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</=
em>the shares, you don=E2=80=99t have to borrow them. And if you=E2=80=99re=
 wrong, and you don=E2=80=99t borrow them, then you are naked short, and th=
at=E2=80=99s bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course here this is silly, it=E2=80=99s a n=
othing. The SEC mentions naked short selling in the press release, but not =
in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvMzQtOTg0OD=
IucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e9fab03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">its order</a>; there is =
no actual allegation that Citadel Securities did any naked short selling at=
 all, and I think it probably did not.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(Also the problem here was symmetrical, and Citadel Securities so=
metimes marked long sales as short because it was selling for customers and=
 thought it was shorter than it was.) The SEC says that =E2=80=9Cthis delay=
 did not benefit Citadel=C2=A0Securities or its trading strategies=E2=80=9D=
; it is a clerical mishap that made some trading data wrong, but it was not=
 intentional, didn=E2=80=99t save Citadel Securities any money, and doesn=
=E2=80=99t seem to have had any effect on anything but the SEC=E2=80=99s re=
cordkeeping.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still.=C2=A0<em>Dumb Money</em>, the GameStop =
movie, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.29=
0424/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFkbGluZS5jb20vMjAyMy8wOS9kdW1iLW1vbmV5LWJveC1vZmZpY2Utc2=
9ueS1yZWxlYXNlLWRhdGUtY2hhbmdlLTEyMzU1MjEwODEv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc5b=
93368" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">will be in wide release</a> this coming weekend, portraying =
Citadel Securities (and Citadel) boss Ken Griffin as a <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3=
MuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzL2F4aW9zLW1hcmtldHMtMzliZjI4ODAtZDg1Ny00YTNiLThlZGYtN=
zE1YThiNTlmNDRkLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBff1c994b" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">cartoon v=
illain</a>. If you think that Ken Griffin is a cartoon villain, there=E2=80=
=99s a decent chance that you are also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDgvZG9uLXQtc3F1ZWV6ZS10aGUtc2hvcnRzP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDA5MjYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBaee5826a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> mad about naked short selling</a>, and, you kno=
w, here=E2=80=99s this!</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">AI in banking</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One somewhat plausible view of artificial inte=
lligence in investment banking is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A robot can do most of the work that =
first-year investment banking analysts do: preparing financial models from =
templates, choosing comparable companies, formatting pitchbooks, cutting le=
ague-table data in exactly the right way to make their bank No. 1, etc.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A robot cannot do most of the work th=
at senior managing directors do: meeting clients face-to-face with a firm h=
andshake and good eye contact, asking them about their kids and their golf =
game, giving strategic advice about merger negotiations and financing optio=
ns, exercising good judgment, tossing aside the pitchbook that the analysts=
 spent sleepless nights preparing to have a heart-to-heart chat about whate=
ver=E2=80=99s on the client=E2=80=99s mind,=C2=A0etc.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not sure that that=E2=80=99s right? Judgi=
ng by actually existing large language models, I would not be stunned if it=
 was easier to program a robot to give confident and sage-sounding strategi=
c advice, and remember the clients=E2=80=99 kids=E2=80=99 names, than it is=
 to program a robot to build financial models with no tolerance for error, =
or perform the dark arts of league-table manipulation. But broadly speaking=
 the junior bankers do some combination of analytical and grunt work, while=
 the senior bankers provide the strategic vision and the personal touch, an=
d it=C2=A0<em>seems=C2=A0</em>like the former would be easier to automate t=
han the latter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investment banking is an odd sort of apprentic=
eship business in that=C2=A0you spend a few years doing the analytical and =
grunt work=C2=A0<em>as training=C2=A0</em>to be strategic and personal. It =
is not <em>obvious=C2=A0</em>that preparing pitchbooks and discounted cash =
flow models would be good preparation for giving clients firm handshakes an=
d nuanced negotiating advice, but that is the way it=E2=80=99s done.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Some (large) number of good junior analysts will not make it as s=
enior investment bankers, because they are good at spreadsheets and formatt=
ing but bad at strategy and handshakes. Some (smaller) number of bad junior=
 analysts will wash out because they are bad at spreadsheets and formatting=
, but if they had scraped through they would have been amazing managing dir=
ectors, with an ingratiating manner and a good grasp of what clients want. =
You need both qualities, in sequence, for some reason.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you give all the analytical and grunt w=
ork to the robot then how do you mold senior investment bankers? I don=E2=
=80=99t know. Insider=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Bianca Chan and Emmalyse Brownstein <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9ob3ctYWktd2lsbC1jaGFuZ2UtdGhlLWludmV=
zdG1lbnQtYmFua2luZy1jYXJlZXItcGF0aC0yMDIzLTk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8d3f8=
77e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"A lot of the work analysts do is very mundane=
. You're doing random Excel stuff or editing a deck or putting logos on a P=
owerpoint," said a first-year investment banking analyst who works on tech =
deals. "As a junior banker you don't critically think. You just do as you'r=
e told." =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"[Artificial intelligence] could be a good thi=
ng for banking if there are some parts that are more automated because it'l=
l get rid of some of the work that takes hours and hours for some of these =
junior guys to go through," said a Wall Street recruiter who specializes in=
 placements in investment banking.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"It could be good for the hours," added the fi=
rst-year analyst.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over at Deutsche Bank, executives like [Tamara=
] Bitticks are seeing the benefits firsthand. The bank has been running doz=
ens of generative AI pilots and hiring hundreds of engineers to transform h=
ow its employees work across the firm. Some of the pilots aim to improve ti=
me-consuming and mundane tasks carried out by juniors in the corporate bank=
, which serves Deutsche's institutional clients, financial services firms, =
and investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One tool set to launch at the beginning of the=
 year will use AI to generate reports senior bankers need to prepare for cl=
ient meetings, Bitticks said. Making one of these reports =E2=80=94 which b=
rief the bankers on leadership changes, company performance, and relevant i=
ndustry trends =E2=80=94 usually takes a team of junior bankers a day or tw=
o to produce, said Bitticks, vice chair in Deutsche's corporate bank.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The new tool will allow these reports to be cr=
eated in just a few keystrokes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The technology will pave the way for "a new wa=
y of being a banker," Bitticks said, and enable juniors to focus on buildin=
g up more analytical skills and soft skills.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"What I struggle with our juniors a lot of tim=
es is they're gathering the information, and they're so consumed with the g=
athering that they don't think about the analyzing," Bitticks told Insider =
in an interview at the Google Cloud Next conference in San Francisco last m=
onth.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is it possible that tediously compiling an upd=
ate on industry trends and client personnel gossip, and then handing it to =
your managing director before she flies off to the meeting,=C2=A0is good pr=
eparation for one day flying to the meeting yourself to give a market updat=
e and gossip with the client? I honestly have no idea. But, like, when the =
analysts are not preparing the pitchbooks for the meetings they are not att=
ending, what=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>they be doing to become more strategic=
 and analytical?</p>
