<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One basic idea in environmental, social and go=
vernance investing is that you should allocate much (100%?) of your investm=
ent portfolio to companies with good ESG credentials, and less (0%?) of you=
r portfolio to companies with bad ESG credentials. You have some reason for=
 liking ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTIvbm90LWV2ZXJ5b25lLWxpa2VzLWVzZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTI2M=
jNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1f=
dGVybT0yMzA5MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98=
8f548d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> main ones</a> are =E2=80=9CI think I will make the world a=
 better place by allocating capital to green companies and withholding capi=
tal from dirty ones,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI think that ESG risk factors are=
 important for long-run financial returns, so companies with good ESG crede=
ntials will outperform those with bad ESG credentials=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that reason counsels you to put more money in good =
ESG stocks and less (or zero) money in bad ESG stocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But zero is a pretty arbitrary cutoff. If it i=
s good to put 100% of your money in good ESG stocks and 0% in bad ESG stock=
s, then isn=E2=80=99t it even better to put 120% of your money in good ESG =
stocks and negative 20% in bad ESG stocks? Shouldn=E2=80=99t you=C2=A0<em>s=
hort=C2=A0</em>companies with bad ESG credentials? I mean, again, your reas=
ons for liking ESG might vary, but either way<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you think it is good for the world=
 to give capital to good ESG companies and deny it to bad ESG companies, th=
en shorting the stocks of bad ESG companies raises their cost of capital ev=
en more, so you should do it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If y=
ou think that bad ESG companies face underappreciated financial risks that =
will drive down their stock prices, then betting against them should be luc=
rative.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is somewhat controversial, because invest=
ing actual money in environmentally friendly companies seems like a straigh=
tforwardly good thing to do, while betting against environmentally bad comp=
anies seems like, you know, financial engineering. I <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDkvdHdlbnR5LXBlcmNlbnQtb2YtYS1=
waWN0dXJlLW9mLWEtZG9nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf035d118" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote once</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It feels very=C2=A0<em>financial</=
em>, using the abstract workings of the financial system to make bold claim=
s about a real-world result. If you are, say, Jim Chanos and you run a shor=
t-focused fund, presumably the overall carbon impact of your portfolio is v=
ery negative (because most companies, in any industry, are using some carbo=
n to make stuff or fly to meetings or whatever, and so if you=E2=80=99re sh=
orting a bunch of companies you have a negative position on a lot of carbon=
 use). Could Jim Chanos just like fly in circles in a private jet while eat=
ing beef and taking long showers and saying =E2=80=9CI am the greatest clim=
ate hero in the history of the world,=E2=80=9D because of his short selling=
? Maybe?</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A further, more nuanced version is: Is it good=
 ESG to short companies that=C2=A0<em>claim=C2=A0</em>to be good at ESG, bu=
t that you think are actually bad at ESG? Not forthrightly dirty coal compa=
nies, but energy companies that pretend to be green and aren=E2=80=99t? A c=
lassic sort of short selling is that a company reports good financial resul=
ts, its stock goes up, you investigate and determine that the company is do=
ing accounting fraud, you short it, you expose the fraud, the stock goes to=
 zero and you get rich. This is all very intuitive: The stock price is high=
 because people think the company is profitable, you bet that it isn=E2=80=
=99t, you win. The mechanism of the trade is that a stock price is the pres=
ent value of the company=E2=80=99s future cash flows, and if the cash flows=
 are fraud then the price is probably too high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if the ESG is fraud? Should you short=
 bad-but-pretending-to-be-good ESG companies, on a theory like =E2=80=9Ca s=
tock price is partly the market=E2=80=99s=C2=A0valuation=C2=A0of a company=
=E2=80=99s ESG behavior, and if the company=E2=80=99s ESG behavior is fake =
then the price is probably too high=E2=80=9D? I mean? It makes some sense, =
right? The stock price is not=C2=A0<em>just=C2=A0</em>the present value of =
the future cash flows. It=E2=80=99s also the present value of what people w=
ill pay you for the stock. And if people mostly want to pay for good ESG pe=
rformance, then the fake-ESG stocks will have high prices now and low price=
s when they are found out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32838589.290424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMjUvc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVycy1tb3V=
udC1hdHRhY2stb24tZXNnLXN0b2Nrcy1ibG9hdGVkLWZyb20tZ3JlZW4taHlwZT9jbXBpZD1CQk=
QwOTI2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlc=
iZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBea5d6e8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">Ishika Mookerjee and Sheryl Tian Tong Lee report</a>=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge fund managers are piling into short posi=
tions in ESG stocks as they hunt for bogus green claims and valuations infl=
ated by record stimulus.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloated prices can be found =E2=80=9Call over =
ESG,=E2=80=9D according to Soren Aandahl, the founder and chief investment =
officer of Texas-based Blue Orca Capital LLC. He says he didn=E2=80=99t set=
 out to target ESG but, here and now, the =E2=80=9Cgreat shorts just happen=
 to be in the ESG space.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cso much capital chasi=
ng=E2=80=9D ESG assets, but there are =E2=80=9Cso few good ideas,=E2=80=9D =
Aandahl said in an interview. He argues that using short positions to expos=
e bad bets =E2=80=9Cwill actually make a positive difference for the earth =
and environment.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As with so much of ESG, one theory here is tha=
t this is a good way to make money: People overpay for fake ESG stocks, so =
you short them and make money as the market corrects. But another theory is=
 that this is=C2=A0<em>good for the earth:=C2=A0</em>People overpay for fak=
e ESG stocks, providing cheap capital to companies that are bad for the ear=
th, but creating an incentive for you to go sniff out the fraud and short t=
hem, increasing their cost of capital and making ESG=E2=80=99s work =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0of rewarding good ESG companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0more efficient.</p>
